The downside:<br>
The DAoC crew are still making &quot;improvements&quot;.  Most of the classes have yet to be &quot;fleshed out&quot; completely and it leaves a bit of uncertainty as to where they are headed.  The classes I have noticed that seem the most popular--and this is purely a visual observation on my part (meaning that reality may be different):<br>
Clerics<br>
Scouts<br>
Paladins<br>
Theurgists<br>
<br>
<br>
For what it's worth:<br>
Kev<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/unizudn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nizudn</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Bruce</span><br> <font color=#5F9EA0>(2/4/02 1:09:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fforgottentruthforeignlegiongeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=886.topic&index=2>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need DAoC info</span><hr size=1> Rick,<br>
<br>
As always, play what you like, but I would have to agree with Monty in all he has said. I will just add a bit of my own views about &quot;tank classes&quot;, since that seems to be where my preference has landed in DAoC...<br>
<br>
I love playing my armsman and he seems to me to be a lot more interesting to play then my EQ warrior ever was. Begining at about level 15 you will be able to link attacks based on your chosen specialty skills (very important to pick a &quot;spec&quot; and concentrate a large portion of your skill points in it...). It's not just mash the attack key and then head down for a fresh bag of pretzels...<br>
<br>
For instance, Tavik has spec'd as a defensive armsman and there are a couple of decent attacks that begin with a block. -Block- / riposte / befuddler... which gives me the ability to do decent 1hs damage ending in a medium stun that costs me fairly low stamina. There are also attacks that cause extra &quot;bleed&quot; damage or that slow down an opponents attack speed. Being able to set up various attack chains is fairly interesting for me. You can also manage agro well with the styles a tank will have.<br>
<br>
There is no perfect template for any class but the generally rule is to spec to at least 2/3 in skills you really want to be good at. <br>
<br>
Even within a singe class there is decent flexibility. The majority of armsmen go &quot;offensive&quot; with a big polearm to do very high damage, but as a defensive arms, I have had some success in being able to protect, stun, block for the primary tank, or just plain old soak up damage... etc.<br>
<br>
As tanks go, I like the armsman, but there is much to be said for Paladins and Mercinaries too. Mercs are the &quot;ranger&quot; class of DAoC and can dish the damage pretty well, easily exceeding the damage output of my defensive armsman. The penalty is lighter armor and somewhat fewer HP's, but if grouped with a plate wearing tank who is working agro, they have pretty much a free pass to max damage.<br>
<br>
I feel that paladins (the &quot;other&quot; plate wearing class) fall somewhere in the middle of the tank range for damage potential and are an excellent group class with the ability to own agro through their heal chant. Having that extra rez'er is nice too...<br>
<br>
As Monty stated, just about every class can solo all the way to 50 if they are willing to be patient enough to do that AND spec your skills correctly. Spreading your spec points out too much or over-concentrating them into something can hurt you significantly and not all classes really get enough spec points to do everything they might want to do. Infiltrators come quickly to mind here...<br>
<br>
If you decide to join the guild after you start, you can do a /who forgot and pick out a few of the classes you are interested in to talk about specifics. There are many great folks to talk to so I will only toss out a couple of quick names regarding classes. I suggest talking with Dunkar about paladins, Grimblade about mercs, and Kalaria about armsmen... er... armswoman in this case!<br>
<br>
